      <abstract>
        <p>Tom Smutzler letter imagines twilight summer marathon through Manhattan (S)</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Certainly, it's premature to get excited about a possible 2012 Olympics in our city (news article, Sept. 12), but try this out:</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Certainly, it's premature to get excited about a possible 2012 Olympics in our city (news article, Sept. 12), but try this out:</p>
        <p>The marathon starts late in the evening to avoid the summer heat, and is run in full darkness and torchlight through the boroughs. However, instead of finishing in Central Park, the runners turn left from Central Park South down the Great White Way, all ablaze and thronged with cheering New Yorkers, on down to the gloried finish at Times Square, the revitalized crossroads of the world.</p>
        <p>Fantasy? Or reality to be?</p>
        <p>TOM SMUTZLER  Bayside, Queens, Sept. 12, 2000</p>
      </block>
